docs.abstract: As many top Democrats eye a run for president in 2020, Elizabeth Warren has all but announced her candidacy, while Joe Biden is planning to campaign up to four days a week this fall for midterm candidates.
docs.snippet: As many top Democrats eye a run for president in 2020, Elizabeth Warren has all but announced her candidacy, while Joe Biden is planning to campaign up to four days a week this fall for midterm candidates.
docs.lead_paragraph: RENO, Nev. — During a campaign-style tour of the West late last month, Senator Elizabeth Warren did not announce she was running for president. But in private events and public speeches, her message about 2020 was as clear as it was rousing.

headline.main: Warren Is Preparing for 2020. So Are Biden, Booker, Harris and Sanders.
headline.print_headline: Warren Is Warming Up for 2020. So Are Many Other Democrats.

docs.lead_paragraph: Can Republicans keep the House? Will Democrats swipe the Senate? Which state is being Made Great Again with the next presidential visit? It’s Monday, Oct. 22, Trump and Cruz are friends again, and there are 15 days until the midterm elections.

docs.abstract: Kris Kobach, a hard-line Trump supporter, could win the Republican nomination for governor, creating intraparty clashes over whether he’s too extreme.
docs.snippet: Kris Kobach, a hard-line Trump supporter, could win the Republican nomination for governor, creating intraparty clashes over whether he’s too extreme.
docs.lead_paragraph: TOPEKA, Kan. — The evolution of the Kansas Republican Party mirrors that of the national party, a rightward shift from the moderation of Dwight D. Eisenhower to the mainstream conservatism of Bob Dole to the small-government absolutism of former Gov. Sam Brownback and Wichita-based Koch Industries.

headline.main: Democrats See an Opening in Kansas if Trump Ally Wins Primary
headline.print_headline: Democrats See Opening in Kansas if Trump Ally Wins Primary

docs.abstract: The clash over Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh’s nomination will leave Democratic senators on the defensive, but it could energize the left in House races.
docs.snippet: The clash over Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh’s nomination will leave Democratic senators on the defensive, but it could energize the left in House races.
docs.lead_paragraph: BOONVILLE, Ind. — Joe Donnelly knew his audience: Addressing a group of camouflage-clad union mine workers and retirees here last weekend, the Democratic senator trumpeted his efforts to protect their pensions and health care, asked attendees to raise their hands if they knew someone with a pre-existing health condition, and made not a single mention of the coming Supreme Court vote that could determine his political fate in November.

headline.main: For Midterms, Supreme Court Political Drama Plays to Its Audience
headline.print_headline: A Court Battle, if Not a Spark, Will Fan the Midterm Flames

byline.original: By Jonathan Martin and Alexander Burns

docs.abstract: The president helped lift South Carolina’s governor and a House candidate in New York, and the Democrats’ liberal wing had its biggest wins yet
docs.snippet: The president helped lift South Carolina’s governor and a House candidate in New York, and the Democrats’ liberal wing had its biggest wins yet
docs.lead_paragraph: COLUMBIA, S.C. — President Trump helped lift a pair of incumbent Republicans locked in difficult races to victory Tuesday while the liberal wing of the Democratic Party scored its most significant successes yet in the primary season, with progressive candidates unseating the fourth-ranking House Democrat and claiming the nominations for governor in Maryland and Colorado.

headline.main: Trump Helps Boost Two Preferred Candidates While Progressive Democrats Gain
headline.print_headline: Trump Buoys Allies, and Liberals Gain Momentum

docs.abstract: In North Dakota and other farm states, the heated debate over the Supreme Court has nationalized the fight for the Senate, elating Republicans and worrying Democrats.

docs.lead_paragraph: RUTLAND, N.D. — When Senator Heidi Heitkamp, a Democrat, and her Republican opponent, Representative Kevin Cramer, put Sunday’s annual Uffda Day celebration on their schedules this year, they most likely thought they would get an earful from voters about tariffs here in the heart of North Dakota’s soybean belt.

headline.main: Court Battle Shifts Political Terrain for Senators in Heartland

docs.lead_paragraph: FRESNO, Calif. — As the drama over offensive comments by two television stars gripped the nation last week, much of the attention focused on President Trump’s Twitter responses: his decision not to condemn the racism in Roseanne Barr’s tweet, and his questioning of whether there was a double standard at play.

headline.main: Is Trump Racist? Is There a Double Standard? California Pastors Debate.
headline.print_headline: In California’s Evangelical Belt, Pastors Talk Trump, Racism and Double Standards
